eval("__webpack_require__.r(__webpack_exports__);\n/* harmony export */ __webpack_require__.d(__webpack_exports__, {\n/* harmony export */   BLOG_POSTS: () => (/* binding */ BLOG_POSTS)\n/* harmony export */ });\nconst BLOG_POSTS = [\n    {\n        slug: \"what-is-panchang\",\n        title: \"What Is Panchang? A Complete Guide to the Hindu Sacred Calendar\",\n        excerpt: \"The Panchang is not just a calendar — it is a window into the cosmic rhythm of the day. Here is what each of its five elements means and why they still matter.\",\n        category: \"Panchang & Astrology\",\n        readTime: \"6 min read\",\n        date: \"March 2026\",\n        sections: [\n            {\n                heading: \"What Does Panchang Mean?\",\n                content: `The word Panchang comes from two Sanskrit words: Pancha (five) and Anga (limb). A Panchang is literally the five-limbed body of the day. Every day in the Vedic tradition is described by five elements — Tithi, Vara, Nakshatra, Yoga, and Karana — and together they tell you the quality of that particular moment in time.\\n\\nFor thousands of years, families consulted the Panchang before naming a child, fixing a wedding date, starting a business, or beginning a journey. Today, even in cities, millions of Indians still check the Panchang — often through an app on their phone — before any significant decision.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Tithi — The Lunar Day\",\n                content: `Tithi is the lunar day, and it is the most important element of the Panchang. Unlike a solar day (which is fixed at 24 hours), a Tithi is the time it takes for the Moon to gain 12 degrees of longitude over the Sun. Since the Moon moves at varying speeds, Tithis can be shorter or longer than a solar day — sometimes two Tithis fall in one day, sometimes a Tithi spans two days.\\n\\nThere are 30 Tithis in a lunar month, divided into two Pakshas (fortnights): Shukla Paksha (the bright half, from new moon to full moon) and Krishna Paksha (the dark half, from full moon to new moon).\\n\\nThe most important Tithis are Purnima (full moon), Amavasya (new moon), Ekadashi (11th), and Chaturdashi (14th). Many festivals — Diwali, Holi, Navratri — are tied to specific Tithis.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Nakshatra — The Birth Star of the Day\",\n                content: `The Moon travels through all 27 Nakshatras (lunar mansions) in approximately 27.3 days. Each Nakshatra occupies 13 degrees and 20 minutes of the sky. The Nakshatra the Moon is in on any given day is considered the Nakshatra of that day.\\n\\nNakshatras are not signs — they are far more specific. Each Nakshatra has a ruling planet, a presiding deity, and a distinct quality. Pushya Nakshatra (ruled by Saturn, presiding deity Brihaspati) is considered one of the most auspicious for beginnings. Vishakha (ruled by Jupiter, deity Indragni) is good for setting goals and achievements.\\n\\nYour birth Nakshatra — the Nakshatra the Moon was in when you were born — is considered your \"Janma Nakshatra\" and is central to your Vedic birth chart.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Yoga — The Quality of the Day\",\n                content: `Yoga in the Panchang context does not mean the physical practice. It is a quality assigned to each day based on the combined movement of the Sun and Moon. There are 27 Yogas, and they range from highly auspicious (Siddhi, Shubha, Brahma) to inauspicious (Vishkambha, Vyatipata, Vaidhriti).\\n\\nThe Yoga is calculated by adding the degrees of the Sun and Moon and dividing by 13°20'. Each Yoga carries its own tone — some days are naturally strong for effort and achievement, others call for caution and stillness.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Karana — The Half-Day\",\n                content: `A Karana is half a Tithi — roughly 6 hours. Each Tithi has two Karanas. There are 11 Karanas in total: 7 that repeat (called Chara, or moveable) and 4 that appear only once in a lunar month (called Sthira, or fixed).\\n\\nKaranas are used for more precise muhurat calculations. Vishti Karana (also called Bhadra) is considered inauspicious and is avoided for important tasks.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Vara — The Day of the Week\",\n                content: `Vara is the simplest element — the day of the week. But in Vedic tradition, each day is ruled by a planet: Sunday by the Sun, Monday by the Moon, Tuesday by Mars, Wednesday by Mercury, Thursday by Jupiter, Friday by Venus, and Saturday by Saturn.\\n\\nThis is the origin of the English day names too (Saturday = Saturn's day, Sunday = Sun's day). The ruling planet of a Vara influences what that day is naturally good for. Thursdays (Guruvara, Jupiter's day) are good for learning and teaching. Fridays (Shukravara, Venus's day) are good for creative work and relationships.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"How to Use the Panchang Today\",\n                content: `You do not need to be an astrologer to use the Panchang. A few simple applications:\\n\\nFor new beginnings: Choose a day with an auspicious Tithi (Pratipada, Dwitiya, Tritiya, Panchami, Saptami, Dashami, Ekadashi, Dwadashi are generally good), a positive Yoga, and avoid Vishti Karana.\\n\\nFor the best time of day: Abhijit Muhurta (the 24-minute window around solar noon) is universally considered auspicious for any beginning.\\n\\nFor caution: Avoid Rahukala, the inauspicious window each day (timing varies by weekday) for starting anything important.\\n\\nAstravedam calculates today's Panchang in real time, with accurate sunrise and sunset timings for your location. Check it each morning to understand the quality of the day ahead.`\n            }\n        ]\n    },\n    {\n        slug: \"kundali-matching-marriage\",\n        title: \"Kundali Matching for Marriage: What Ashtakoota Really Means\",\n        excerpt: \"An 18/36 score does not mean incompatibility. Understanding what the eight kootas actually measure will completely change how you read a kundali match.\",\n        category: \"Kundali & Astrology\",\n        readTime: \"8 min read\",\n        date: \"March 2026\",\n        sections: [\n            {\n                heading: \"Why Kundali Matching Still Matters\",\n                content: `Millions of Indian marriages begin with kundali matching (also called kundli milan or guna milan). Even many modern, urban couples who do not take astrology seriously find their families asking for it. But most people do not actually understand what is being measured — they only see the score out of 36 and react to it.\\n\\nThis is unfortunate, because the Ashtakoota system is actually a sophisticated compatibility analysis that considers psychological compatibility, health, sexual harmony, financial trajectory, and temperament — not just \"cosmic harmony\" in some vague sense.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"The Eight Kootas Explained\",\n                content: `Ashtakoota means \"eight groups.\" Each koota scores compatibility on a specific dimension:\\n\\n1. Varna (1 point) — Spiritual orientation and work ethic. Often misread as \"caste matching\" — what it actually measures is whether both people have similar values and drive.\\n\\n2. Vashya (2 points) — Mutual attraction and influence. Who naturally leads, who follows, and whether that dynamic is healthy.\\n\\n3. Tara (3 points) — Health and longevity compatibility. Based on the distance between the two Nakshatras.\\n\\n4. Yoni (4 points) — Sexual and physical compatibility. Each Nakshatra is associated with an animal, and the compatibility of the two animals (friendly, neutral, or hostile) reflects physical harmony.\\n\\n5. Graha Maitri (5 points) — Mental and emotional compatibility. Based on the ruling planets of each person's Moon Nakshatra — are these planets friends, neutral, or enemies?\\n\\n6. Gana (6 points) — Temperament. Three types: Deva (divine/gentle), Manava (human/practical), Rakshasa (intense/ambitious). Best matches are same-Gana; Deva-Manava also works well.\\n\\n7. Bhakoot (7 points) — Financial and family prosperity together. This is the most controversial koota. Low scores here generate the most fear, but many astrologers say Bhakoot doshas can be nullified by other strong placements.\\n\\n8. Nadi (8 points) — Genetic and health compatibility, particularly related to children's health. Nadi dosha (both partners having the same Nadi) is considered the most significant concern.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"What Score Is Actually Enough?\",\n                content: `Traditional texts recommend a minimum of 18/36 for marriage. Many modern practitioners lower this to 14-15 in cases of strong mutual compatibility in other areas of the chart.\\n\\nBut the score is only half the picture. A couple scoring 28/36 with Nadi dosha might face more real challenges than a couple scoring 20/36 without it. The quality of the individual kootas matters more than the total.\\n\\nAlso critical: the overall chart comparison (comparing Lagna lords, 7th house, navamsha charts) is equally important and often overlooked when people focus only on the Guna score.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Doshas — When Not to Panic\",\n                content: `Manglik dosha (Mars in the 1st, 4th, 7th, 8th, or 12th house) is the most feared — and most misunderstood — placement in Indian marriage astrology. Roughly 50% of the population is \"Manglik\" in some reading of the rule. Most serious astrologers consider only the 1st, 7th, and 8th house placements significant, and even those can be balanced when both partners are Manglik or when Mars is otherwise well-placed.\\n\\nNadi dosha is more genuinely significant, but it too can be examined in context. If the Moon is placed in different signs in the two charts, some traditions nullify Nadi dosha entirely.\\n\\nThe larger point: every horoscope has \"doshas.\" A good astrologer looks at the whole picture, not just flags individual placements.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"What Kundali Matching Cannot Tell You\",\n                content: `No chart analysis can tell you whether two people will be happy together. It cannot measure communication skills, emotional maturity, shared goals, or the willingness to do the actual work of a relationship. These are human qualities, not planetary ones.\\n\\nKundali matching is best used as one lens among many — a way to identify areas that might need extra attention, not as a verdict on whether a relationship can work. Generations of happily married couples had low Guna scores. And generations of people with perfect 36/36 matches did not stay together.\\n\\nUse it as information. Do not use it as permission or rejection.`\n            }\n        ]\n    },\n    {\n        slug: \"sade-sati-remedies\",\n        title: \"Sade Sati and Shani Dhaiya: What Actually Happens and What to Do\",\n        excerpt: \"Sade Sati is not a curse. It is a 7.5-year period of Saturn's scrutiny — and those who use it well often emerge with the clearest sense of purpose of their lives.\",\n        category: \"Planets & Remedies\",\n        readTime: \"7 min read\",\n        date: \"February 2026\",\n        sections: [\n            {\n                heading: \"What Is Sade Sati?\",\n                content: `Sade Sati literally means \"seven and a half\" in Hindi. It refers to the approximately 7.5-year period when Saturn (Shani) transits through three consecutive zodiac signs — the sign before your Moon sign, the sign of your Moon, and the sign after your Moon sign. Saturn spends about 2.5 years in each sign, which adds up to 7.5 years total.\\n\\nThis is one of the most discussed and feared transits in Vedic astrology. Families warn about it. People perform elaborate rituals to ward off its effects. But the fear is largely exaggerated, and in many cases, counterproductive.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"What Sade Sati Actually Does\",\n                content: `Saturn is the planet of discipline, karma, and reality. When it moves through your Moon sign area, it brings scrutiny to the emotional and mental landscape of your life (the Moon represents the mind and inner world).\\n\\nThe three phases of Sade Sati each have a different character:\\n\\nFirst phase (Saturn in the sign before your Moon): External disruptions — career changes, shifts in relationships, health issues in the family. Life starts asking questions.\\n\\nSecond phase (Saturn over your Moon): The internal phase. This is often the hardest. Mental heaviness, self-doubt, a sense of being burdened. But this is also the phase of deepest self-examination and genuine growth.\\n\\nThird phase (Saturn in the sign after your Moon): Consolidation. Life begins to stabilize. The lessons of the first two phases start showing their value.\\n\\nShani Dhaiya (also called Elinati Shani or Kantaka Shani) is a shorter 2.5-year transit when Saturn moves through the 4th or 8th house from your natal Moon. It shares some characteristics with the second phase of Sade Sati.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Historical Perspective\",\n                content: `Many of the most significant periods of achievement in people's lives — major career shifts, important creative work, spiritual transformation — have coincided with Sade Sati. The pressure of Saturn forces clarity. When Saturn asks \"what do you actually want?\" and strips away the comfortable distractions, many people finally get the answer.\\n\\nThis does not mean Sade Sati is easy. It is not. But \"hard\" and \"bad\" are not the same thing.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Practical Remedies\",\n                content: `These are remedies from the Vedic tradition, offered not as magical fixes but as practices that focus the mind and reinforce the right qualities Saturn is trying to teach:\\n\\nShani Mantra: \"Om Sham Shanaischaraya Namah\" — chanted 108 times on Saturdays, ideally at dawn. The mantra itself is less important than the consistent practice of sitting quietly and directing your intention toward patience and discipline.\\n\\nHanuman Worship: Tuesdays and Saturdays are good days to read the Hanuman Chalisa. Hanuman is considered a powerful counterbalance to Saturn's harshness — devotion (bhakti) softens the planet of karma.\\n\\nService (Seva): Saturn represents the common worker, the patient laborer. Acts of service — volunteering, feeding the hungry, supporting those in difficulty — are considered among the most effective Saturn remedies. Not as ritual, but as genuine action.\\n\\nSimplicity: Saturn dislikes excess and pride. During Sade Sati, a simpler life — less spending, less accumulation, more discipline — genuinely reduces friction.\\n\\nBlue sapphire (Neelam): Only to be worn after proper consultation with an experienced astrologer. This gemstone can amplify Saturn's energy dramatically, which is beneficial if your Saturn is well-placed but very difficult if it is not.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"What to Avoid During Sade Sati\",\n                content: `More important than what to do is what not to do. Saturn punishes shortcuts, dishonesty, and cutting corners more harshly during this period. Avoid:\\n\\nMaking major decisions out of fear or impatience. Saturn rewards those who wait.\\n\\nNeglecting responsibilities. Sade Sati amplifies the consequences of laziness or carelessness.\\n\\nIgnoring health. The period often surfaces neglected health matters. Pay attention.\\n\\nReacting to every difficulty as a sign of cosmic punishment. Most of what happens during Sade Sati is normal life — circumstances that would have occurred regardless, perhaps slightly intensified.`\n            }\n        ]\n    },\n    {\n        slug: \"powerful-mantras-daily-life\",\n        title: \"10 Powerful Mantras for Daily Life: When to Chant and Why\",\n        excerpt: \"A mantra is not a magic spell. It is a technology of attention — these ten mantras, used consistently, can genuinely shift how the mind moves through the day.\",\n        category: \"Mantras & Practice\",\n        readTime: \"9 min read\",\n        date: \"March 2026\",\n        sections: [\n            {\n                heading: \"What Makes a Mantra Work\",\n                content: `The Sanskrit word mantra comes from \"manas\" (mind) and \"tra\" (tool or instrument). A mantra is literally a tool for the mind. The sound itself is not magical in the way most people think — the power comes from repetition, intention, and the quality of attention you bring to the practice.\\n\\nThat said, the Vedic tradition holds that certain sounds have specific vibrational qualities that affect the mind and body. Modern sound research has found that repetitive chanting does measurably reduce cortisol, slow the breath, and activate the parasympathetic nervous system. You do not need to choose between the traditional and the scientific understanding — both are pointing at something real.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"1. Gayatri Mantra\",\n                content: `Om Bhur Bhuvah Svah / Tat Savitur Varenyam / Bhargo Devasya Dhimahi / Dhiyo Yo Nah Prachodayat\\n\\nTranslation: We meditate on the divine light of the Sun. May it illuminate and guide our intellect.\\n\\nBest time: Sunrise, ideally facing east. 3, 11, or 108 repetitions.\\n\\nThis is the most sacred mantra in the Vedic tradition, from the Rigveda. It is a prayer for illuminated intelligence — not mere cleverness, but the wisdom to see clearly. Use it before any serious mental work or decision-making.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"2. Mahamrityunjaya Mantra\",\n                content: `Om Tryambakam Yajamahe / Sugandhim Pushtivardhanam / Urvarukamiva Bandhanan / Mrityor Mukshiya Maamritat\\n\\nTranslation: We worship Shiva, the three-eyed one, who nurtures all. As a cucumber detaches naturally from the vine, may we be liberated from the cycle of death and decay, and be granted immortality.\\n\\nBest time: Any time, but particularly powerful during illness, fear, or major transitions. 108 repetitions.\\n\\nThis Shiva mantra is used for healing, protection, and fearlessness. It is recited at hospitals, during serious illness, and before surgeries in the Vedic tradition. Its effect on the nervous system is calming and stabilizing.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"3. Om Namah Shivaya\",\n                content: `Om Namah Shivaya — the five-syllable Panchakshara mantra (Na Ma Shi Va Ya) representing the five elements of nature.\\n\\nTranslation: I bow to Shiva / I honor what is real within me.\\n\\nBest time: Morning or evening. Can be chanted continuously — it is one of the easiest mantras to integrate into daily activity.\\n\\nThis is one of the most powerful and accessible mantras in the Hindu tradition. It does not require elaborate preparation or initiation. The simple act of repeating it with some awareness of breath creates a centering effect that many practitioners describe as immediately noticeable.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"4. Ganesha Mantra\",\n                content: `Om Gam Ganapataye Namah\\n\\nTranslation: Salutations to Ganesha, the remover of obstacles.\\n\\nBest time: Before any new beginning — a new project, a new day, a difficult conversation.\\n\\nChant 21 or 108 times. Ganesha is traditionally invoked first before any Vedic ritual or significant beginning. This mantra is particularly useful when you feel mentally blocked, stuck in indecision, or facing a threshold you cannot seem to cross.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"5. Lakshmi Beej Mantra\",\n                content: `Om Shreem Mahalakshmiyei Namah\\n\\nTranslation: Salutations to Mahalakshmi. (Shreem is the beej mantra of Lakshmi.)\\n\\nBest time: Fridays, at dawn or dusk. 108 repetitions.\\n\\nShreem is the seed sound of Lakshmi — of abundance, beauty, and grace. This mantra is used for attracting prosperity, but the Lakshmi tradition is clear: prosperity follows dharma. The mantra works best when combined with honest effort and generosity.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"6. Saraswati Mantra\",\n                content: `Om Aim Saraswatyei Namah\\n\\nTranslation: Salutations to Saraswati. (Aim is her beej mantra.)\\n\\nBest time: Before studying, creative work, or any intellectual endeavor. Wednesdays.\\n\\nStudents have used this mantra for millennia before examinations. But its real application is broader — any time you need clarity of thought, creative inspiration, or the ability to communicate something difficult. The beej sound \"Aim\" is associated with the activation of intelligence.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"7. Hanuman Chalisa (Opening Verse)\",\n                content: `Shri Guru Charan Saroj Raj / Nij Man Mukur Sudhari / Barnau Raghuvar Bimal Yash / Jo Dayaku Phal Chari\\n\\nThe full Hanuman Chalisa (40 verses by Tulsidas) takes 10-15 minutes to recite. The complete text is one of the most chanted texts in India.\\n\\nBest time: Tuesdays and Saturdays, or any time you feel fear, anxiety, or face a situation requiring courage.\\n\\nThe Chalisa is not a begging prayer — it is a praise poem that recounts Hanuman's deeds and character. Reciting it regularly instills the qualities it describes: courage, devotion, clarity, and the understanding that one's strength comes from surrendering to something larger than the ego.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"8. Navagraha Shanti Mantra\",\n                content: `Om Navagraha Devaya Namah (simple combined salutation)\\n\\nOr each planet individually: Om Suryaya Namah (Sun), Om Chandraya Namah (Moon), Om Mangalaya Namah (Mars), Om Budhaya Namah (Mercury), Om Brihaspataye Namah (Jupiter), Om Shukraya Namah (Venus), Om Shanaischaraya Namah (Saturn), Om Rahave Namah (Rahu), Om Ketave Namah (Ketu).\\n\\nBest time: At sunrise, facing east, chanting each planetary mantra 9 or 27 times.\\n\\nThis practice acknowledges and honors all nine planetary influences rather than trying to suppress or appease them. The daily awareness of the planets and their qualities is itself a form of attentiveness that the tradition considers valuable.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"On Consistent Practice\",\n                content: `Any mantra practiced for 40 consecutive days (a \"sadhana\") creates a noticeably different quality of experience than occasional chanting. The number 108 has mathematical significance in Vedic astronomy (the distance from Earth to the Sun is approximately 108 solar diameters; the distance from Earth to the Moon is approximately 108 lunar diameters). Japa malas (prayer beads) have 108 beads for this reason.\\n\\nStart with one mantra, one time of day, and do it consistently for a month. Notice what changes.`\n            }\n        ]\n    },\n    {\n        slug: \"navagraha-planets-vedic-astrology\",\n        title: \"Navagraha: The 9 Planets in Vedic Astrology and Their Remedies\",\n        excerpt: \"Rahu and Ketu are not physical planets — they are mathematical points. Understanding all nine grahas, including the shadow planets, demystifies most of what people fear about their chart.\",\n        category: \"Planets & Remedies\",\n        readTime: \"10 min read\",\n        date: \"January 2026\",\n        sections: [\n            {\n                heading: \"What Is a Graha?\",\n                content: `The Sanskrit word graha is often translated as \"planet,\" but its root meaning is \"that which grasps.\" A graha grasps the mind and influences behavior. Vedic astrology works with nine grahas: the Sun, Moon, Mars, Mercury, Jupiter, Venus, Saturn, Rahu, and Ketu. The outer planets (Uranus, Neptune, Pluto) are not used in classical Jyotish.\\n\\nEach graha rules specific areas of life, a day of the week, colors, gemstones, deities, and materials. Understanding these associations is the foundation of Vedic astrology.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Surya (Sun)\",\n                content: `Day: Sunday. Color: Gold/Orange. Deity: Surya, Vishnu.\\n\\nThe Sun represents the soul (Atman), the father, authority, health, and vitality. A strong Sun gives confidence, leadership, and good health. A weak or afflicted Sun can manifest as low self-esteem, problems with authority figures, or weak immunity.\\n\\nRemedy: Surya Namaskar at sunrise. Chant \"Om Suryaya Namah\" 108 times on Sundays. Offer water to the rising sun (Arghya) each morning.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Chandra (Moon)\",\n                content: `Day: Monday. Color: White, Silver. Deity: Shiva (as Chandrashekhara), Parvati.\\n\\nThe Moon represents the mind, emotions, mother, and the body's fluids. A strong Moon gives emotional stability, good memory, and a nurturing personality. A weak Moon can manifest as anxiety, depression, insomnia, or strained relationship with the mother.\\n\\nRemedy: Fasting on Mondays. Wearing white or silver on Mondays. Milk offerings to Shiva on Mondays. The Moon is strongest in Cancer and Taurus.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Mangala (Mars)\",\n                content: `Day: Tuesday. Color: Red. Deity: Kartikeya (Murugan), Hanuman.\\n\\nMars represents energy, courage, siblings, real estate, and the blood. Strong Mars gives drive, athletic ability, and decisiveness. Afflicted Mars can show as anger, accidents, conflicts, and impulsive decisions.\\n\\nRemedy: Hanuman worship on Tuesdays. Red coral (only after astrological consultation). Offering red flowers to Hanuman. Regular physical exercise is a genuine Mars remedy — it channels the energy properly.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Budha (Mercury)\",\n                content: `Day: Wednesday. Color: Green. Deity: Vishnu.\\n\\nMercury governs communication, intelligence, trade, siblings, and the nervous system. A strong Mercury gives quick thinking, eloquence, and business acumen. Weak Mercury can mean poor communication, indecision, or problems with contracts and paperwork.\\n\\nRemedy: Reciting Vishnu Sahasranama on Wednesdays. Green moong (lentils) on Wednesdays. Emerald (after consultation). Budha is the planet of students, merchants, and writers.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Brihaspati (Jupiter)\",\n                content: `Day: Thursday. Color: Yellow. Deity: Brahma, Dakshinamurthy (teaching form of Shiva).\\n\\nJupiter is the most benefic planet in Vedic astrology. It governs wisdom, higher education, dharma, children, wealth, and spirituality. A strong Jupiter gives generosity, wisdom, and good fortune. A weak Jupiter can mean problems with children, lack of faith, or poor judgment.\\n\\nRemedy: Yellow clothing on Thursdays. Worship of the Guru. Offering yellow flowers to Jupiter. Study of sacred texts. Jupiter is exalted in Cancer.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Shukra (Venus)\",\n                content: `Day: Friday. Color: White, Pink. Deity: Lakshmi.\\n\\nVenus governs love, beauty, luxury, arts, marriage, and vehicles. A strong Venus gives charm, artistic sensitivity, and happy relationships. A weak Venus can manifest as relationship problems, financial instability (related to luxury spending), or poor aesthetic sense.\\n\\nRemedy: Lakshmi worship on Fridays. White flowers. Diamond or white sapphire (after consultation). Venus is strengthened by gratitude and generosity.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Shani (Saturn)\",\n                content: `Day: Saturday. Color: Dark Blue, Black. Deity: Yama, Hanuman (as protector).\\n\\nSaturn is the slowest-moving of the classical planets and the most feared — usually unjustly. Saturn governs discipline, karma, longevity, the working class, old age, and chronic conditions. A strong Saturn gives extraordinary endurance, discipline, and the ability to build lasting things. A weak Saturn manifests as laziness, chronic illness, or an inability to face consequences.\\n\\nRemedy: Shani mantra on Saturdays. Service to the poor and elderly. Iron or steel objects. Blue sapphire — only after careful consultation, as this stone amplifies whatever Saturn represents in your chart.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Rahu — The North Node\",\n                content: `Day: Associated with Saturdays. Color: Smoky, Ultraviolet. Deity: Durga (for protection).\\n\\nRahu is not a physical planet — it is the ascending lunar node, the point where the Moon's orbit crosses the ecliptic going northward. In Vedic myth, Rahu is the severed head of the demon Svarbhanu, who drank the nectar of immortality and was beheaded by Vishnu before he could swallow it.\\n\\nRahu represents ambition, obsession, illusion, foreign lands, technology, and unconventional paths. A strong Rahu gives exceptional ambition and the ability to succeed in unusual fields. Afflicted Rahu can bring confusion, deception (including self-deception), addictions, and a restless dissatisfaction.\\n\\nRemedy: Durga worship. Reciting Durga Chalisa. Rahu responds well to clarity and honesty — wherever there is deception in your life, Rahu's effects intensify.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Ketu — The South Node\",\n                content: `Day: Associated with Tuesdays. Color: Gray, Spotted. Deity: Ganesha, Bhairava.\\n\\nKetu is the descending lunar node — the severed body of the same demon, still moving by momentum. Where Rahu is hungry and reaching forward, Ketu is detached and looking inward. Ketu represents past-life karma, spirituality, liberation (moksha), intuition, and sudden events.\\n\\nKetu conjunct a planet often gives an unusual relationship with that planet's significations — either exceptional attainment or total disinterest. Ketu in the 12th house (house of liberation) is considered favorable for spiritual seekers.\\n\\nRemedy: Ganesha worship. Ketu responds to non-attachment. Simplicity, meditation, and reduced material desire are genuinely effective Ketu remedies.`\n            }\n        ]\n    },\n    {\n        slug: \"vastu-shastra-home-guide\",\n        title: \"Vastu Shastra for Your Home: Principles That Actually Matter\",\n        excerpt: \"Most Vastu advice online is vague superstition. These are the principles that have logical grounding in climate, geography, and human psychology — applicable even in a modern apartment.\",\n        category: \"Vastu & Lifestyle\",\n        readTime: \"8 min read\",\n        date: \"February 2026\",\n        sections: [\n            {\n                heading: \"What Vastu Shastra Actually Is\",\n                content: `Vastu Shastra is the ancient Indian science of architecture and spatial arrangement. The word \"Vastu\" means dwelling or site; \"Shastra\" means science or scripture. It is a system developed over millennia for arranging living and working spaces in harmony with natural forces — the direction of sunlight, wind patterns, the earth's magnetic field, and the flow of water.\\n\\nMany Vastu principles have a rational, climate-specific basis for the Indian subcontinent. The instruction to have the kitchen in the southeast (direction of the morning sun, ruled by Agni, the fire deity) is not magical — east-facing kitchens in the northern hemisphere get morning light, which naturally disinfects and keeps the food preparation area well-lit at breakfast time.\\n\\nOther Vastu rules are more symbolic and cultural. A good approach is to apply those with clear logic and treat the symbolic ones as optional aesthetic guidance.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Which Direction to Sleep\",\n                content: `This is the most searched Vastu question, and the most consistent answer across traditions is: head to the south, feet to the north.\\n\\nThe reasoning: the Earth's magnetic field runs north to south. The human body, like a weak magnet, has its own polarity. Sleeping with your head to the south aligns you with the field rather than against it. Multiple sleep studies have found that people with south-facing heads report better sleep quality on average.\\n\\nDo not sleep with your head to the north: this is considered the direction of the magnetic poles and is associated with disrupted sleep and even health issues in traditional texts. East is acceptable (and actually traditional in many families). West is generally neutral.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"The Prayer Room (Pooja Room)\",\n                content: `The northeast corner (Ishanya disha) is traditionally considered the most sacred corner of a home — where the sun's energy is pure in the morning and the earth's energy is considered most stable. This is the ideal location for a prayer room or prayer alcove.\\n\\nIf you live in an apartment and cannot dedicate a room, a small altar on the northeast wall of your living room or bedroom serves the same purpose. The main idol or image should face west or east (so you face east or west when praying — toward the rising sun or toward the deity).\\n\\nAvoid placing the prayer room directly adjacent to a bathroom, or below a staircase. These are not superstitions but practical sensibilities about cleanliness and the psychological quality of the space.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Kitchen Placement and Direction\",\n                content: `Southeast is traditional for the kitchen, ruled by Agni (fire). Practically, this means morning sunlight enters the kitchen, the cook usually faces east or north while cooking (both considered auspicious), and the heat of the kitchen does not dominate the sleeping or living areas (which are typically northwest or southwest).\\n\\nAvoid cooking while facing south — this is the direction of Yama (death) in Vedic cosmology, and practically speaking, it orients you away from natural light in most Indian home configurations.\\n\\nIf your kitchen is already in a \"wrong\" direction and you cannot move it, ensure it is clean, well-lit, and well-ventilated. Vastu also teaches that the energy of the cook — their mental state while cooking — is more important than the kitchen's orientation.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Entrance Direction\",\n                content: `The main entrance of a home is one of the most important Vastu elements. North and east-facing entrances are considered most auspicious because they receive morning sunlight, which brings natural light and energy into the home throughout the day.\\n\\nSouth-facing entrances are often flagged as problematic in Vastu, but this concern is vastly overstated. Many successful homes and businesses have south-facing entrances. What matters more is that the entrance is clean, unobstructed, and well-lit. A blocked or cluttered entrance — regardless of direction — creates what Vastu calls \"Nazar dosha\" (obstacle at the threshold).\\n\\nThe area immediately outside and inside the main entrance should always be clean and free of clutter. This is one Vastu rule that is almost universally applicable and makes obvious practical sense.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"Colors by Direction\",\n                content: `Vastu assigns colors to directions based on their elemental and planetary associations:\\n\\nNorth (Mercury, Water): greens and blues\\nNortheast (Jupiter): yellow or cream\\nEast (Sun): light orange or pale yellow\\nSoutheast (Venus/Fire): pink, orange\\nSouth (Mars): red, pink\\nSouthwest (Earth/Saturn): brown, beige, grey\\nWest (Saturn): blue, grey\\nNorthwest (Moon/Air): white, silver\\n\\nFor practical use: paint the bedroom in calming blues and greens (associated with north/water). Avoid bright red in sleeping areas. The prayer corner benefits from yellow or saffron. The kitchen naturally suits orange and warm tones.\\n\\nThese are gentle guidelines, not rules. Any color used thoughtfully is better than a \"correct\" color used without care.`\n            },\n            {\n                heading: \"What to Do in an Apartment\",\n                content: `Most apartments cannot satisfy all Vastu requirements — the entrance faces where the building architect decided it would face. Here is a pragmatic approach:\\n\\n1. Control what you can: sleep direction, prayer corner placement, kitchen cleanliness, and the entrance area.\\n\\n2. Use Vastu symbolically: a small copper or brass pyramid at the northeast corner, a clear bowl of rock salt in a problematic corner (changed weekly), or a Swastik symbol at the entrance are traditional \"remedies\" that cost nothing and maintain awareness of the principles.\\n\\n3. Prioritize: clutter is the single greatest Vastu issue in modern homes. Before worrying about directions, remove what is not needed. An uncluttered home in any direction will have better energy than a perfectly Vastu-compliant one that is chaotic and full of unused objects.\\n\\n4. Do not panic about Vastu doshas: most \"problems\" identified by Vastu consultants have simple remedies and are not catastrophic. The tradition itself says that the dharmic conduct of the people who live in a home is more powerful than any directional placement.`\n            }\n        ]\n    }\n];\n//# sourceURL=[module]\n//# sourceMappingURL=data:application/json;charset=utf-8;base64,\n//# sourceURL=webpack-internal:///./src/data/blogs.js\n");

